Questions:
What will happen to the data collected from you if you choose to withdraw from the eHOPE study?
A) The data collected will be destroyed and not used in the study;
B) The data collected up to the point of withdrawal will still be used in the study;
C) Withdrawing from the study will result in a penalty fee;
D) Your child's future treatment will be affected if you withdraw.

Correct answer: B

Which component of the eHOPE study is considered experimental?
A) Routine care and information provided by healthcare professionals during scheduled appointments;
B) Access to a website with general information about childhood cancers;
C) The use of the eHOPE website to provide targeted information support and activities for parents of children with haematological cancer;
D) Completion of questionnaires at the beginning and end of the study.

Correct answer: C

Who will have access to your personal and medical information obtained during the study, and how will your confidentiality be protected?
A) Only the principal investigator and no one else; 
B) Study staff, qualified monitors and auditors, the sponsor or its affiliates, and governmental or regulatory authorities, with all personal details treated as strictly confidential;
C) All hospital staff and the general public;
D) Only other participants in the study.

Correct answer: B
